'''Joshua Milton Blahyi''' (born 30 September 1971), better known by his [[Pseudonym|nom de guerre]] '''General Butt Naked''', is a Liberian evangelical preacher, writer and former warlord best known for his actions during the [[First Liberian Civil War]]. During the conflict, Blahyi led a group of soldiers which fought on the side of the anti-rebel group [[United Liberation Movement of Liberia for Democracy]] (ULIMO) before [[Conversion to Christianity|converting to Christianity]] and becoming a pastor in 1996.

Born in the Liberian capital of [[Monrovia]] to a [[Krahn people|Krahn]] family, Blahyi was handed by his father to several tribal elders who initiated him as a [[high priest]] in 1982 at the age of eleven. After Liberian military officer [[Samuel Doe]] staged a [[1980 Liberian coup d'état|coup d'état]] against President [[William Tolbert|William R. Tolbert]] in 1980, the new regime employed Blahyi to perform [[black magic]] rituals at the [[Executive Mansion, Monrovia|presidential palace]] in [[Monrovia]] to help him win the [[1985 Liberian general election|1985 general election]].

In 1989, [[National Patriotic Front of Liberia]] (NPFL) rebel leader [[Charles Taylor (Liberian politician)|Charles Taylor]] launched a rebellion against Doe's regime, sparking a [[First Liberian Civil War|civil war]]. Blahyi joined ULIMO, a rival militia group, and operated primarily around the Monrovia area. During the conflict, Blahyi and his men, a group of soldiers known as the Naked Base Commandos, fought without clothing and perpetrated numerous atrocities, including [[child sacrifice]] and [[Human cannibalism|cannibalism]].

Blahyi abandoned his life as a warlord and turned to preaching after undergoing a religious conversion in 1996, attributing these actions to receiving a [[Visions of Jesus and Mary|vision of Jesus]]. In 2008, Blahyi testified at the [[Truth and Reconciliation Commission (Liberia)|Liberian Truth and Reconciliation Commission]], claiming that his victims numbered at least 20,000 individuals. The public testimony brought mixed reactions and led to international attention, leading Blahyi to be featured in several documentaries.

==Early life==
[[File:Samuel Kanyon Doe - Liberian.jpg|thumb|140px|Blahyi fought on the side of [[Samuel Doe]] (pictured) during the First Liberian Civil War.]]

Joshua Milton Blahyi was born on 30 September 1971, in [[Monrovia]], [[Liberia]]. He was born into a [[Krahn people|Krahn]] family, some of whom resided in [[Sinoe County]], located in the south of the country; among the Krahn people, belief in [[child sacrifice]] and [[black magic]] was common.{{sfn|Margaritoff|2021}} When he was seven years old, his father granted parental control over him to several Krahn elders, who arranged for Blahyi to be a [[warrior]] and initiated him as a [[high priest]] in 1982, when he was at the age of eleven.{{sfn|Margaritoff|2021}}{{sfn|Paye-Layleh|2008}}

As Blahyi noted in his memoirs, the role of high priest included overseeing [[human sacrifice]]s. Blahyi, like other Krahn priests, would use [[Vision (spirituality)|visions]] to determine which individual would be sacrificed. After receiving the vision, Blahyi would "give the victim’s last name to its [[Elder (administrative title)|village elders]]", who would then lead a procession to the sacrifice victim's house, abducting and then sacrificing them atop an [[altar]]; after Blahyi stated an [[invocation]], the victim would then be ritually dismembered.{{sfn|Margaritoff|2021}}

In 1980, [[Armed Forces of Liberia]] (AFL) master-sergeant [[Samuel Doe]] staged a [[1980 Liberian coup d'état|coup d'état]], overthrowing then-President [[William Tolbert]].{{sfn|Dash|1980}} Blahyi claims that Doe employed him to perform black magic rituals to influence the [[1985 Liberian general election]], although Doe's victory relied more practically on destroying most of the opposition's ballots.{{sfn|Tabor|2016}} Blahyi later explained his support for Doe as being based on a sense of tribal loyalty, because they were both members of the same ethnic group.{{sfn|Paye-Layleh|2008}}

